UNDIAGNOSED FATALITIES - DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: (BAHORUCO) LEPTOSPIROSIS
SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 4 Nov 2009
Source: El Nuevo Diario [in Spanish, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
<http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=174445>


The public health secretary, Bautista Rojas Gomez, confirmed that lab tests
from the people who died in El Salado, Galvan Municipality, Bahoruco
province, indicated that the deaths were caused by leptospirosis.

He explained that specimens were sent to the Centers for Disease Control
[and Prevention] in Atlanta [Georgia], USA to obtain a definitive diagnosis.

He said that he has maintained direct contact with the health authorities
in the Sur [South] Region, and specialists have been sent to the area,
where they have established a strict sanitary control. He said that several
of the affected individuals had been discharged to their homes and that the
22 who remain in hospital under treatment are in stable condition.

"The situation is under control, and we hope that there will be no further
deaths from the disease. Our epidemiologists and public health
professionals have worked hard over the last few days in order to resolve
the problem," he said and added that the work has been carried out since
the weekend [31 Oct-1 Nov 2009], when they received information that a
significant number of residents of El Salado showed symptoms of disease.

He claimed that more than 100 samples were taken from residents of
different communities in the Sur Region by a mobile laboratory sent by the
State Secretariat of Health as part of control actions against
leptospirosis and other diseases.

He said the team of specialists was reinforced with psychiatrists and
psychologists, who provide care for families impacted by the disease and
that staff from the Department of Environmental Health have been working on
rodent [rats] control, one of the animal transmitters of leptospirosis.

The official said that since the outbreak has been controlled, tranquility
has begun to return to the communities of Bahoruco and Barahona provinces.

In Barahona, 21 persons, including 15 children and 6 adults from of El
Salado, in the municipality of Galvan, continue to be hospitalized in the
Jaime Mota regional university hospital in this city. They were affected by
a virus, supposedly influenza, although not yet specified by the public
health authorities. Dr Gilberto Ariel Suero Cavallo, director of the health
center, said that so far, approximately 33 patients have been treated in
the hospital, all natives of that locality in Bahoruco province.

"We currently have 21 patients, of which 15 are children and 6 are adults,
4 men and 2 women. Of the children, the youngest is 8 years old, and all
have been admitted with symptoms of fever after the outbreak in Salado," he
said and added that the patients are stable, and "They have had specimens
taken for dengue and leptospirosis in order to determine what type of
infection is responsible for the outbreak."

Dr Suero Cavallo said that many experts think that the outbreak involves
one type of dengue, "but until we have definitive evidence, we cannot say
what the true diagnosis is."

He indicated that patients in this hospital are being closely monitored.
"None of the patients are in serious but rather stable condition." He said
that they expect all patients to be discharged to their homes in good
health over the coming days.

The official said the health center is providing all essential services so
that patients regain their health as soon as possible, so they are
monitored and on hydration, which is crucial in these types of diseases.

In the community of El Salado of Galvan municipality, 2 people have died
from a rare disease that has not been identified yet by the Public Health
Authorities.

One of the people died in El Salado and the other in the Jaime Mota
regional university hospital, where others have been hospitalized and under
medical observation for several days.

[byline: Teuddy A Sanchez]

